A number is a power of another number if it can be expressed in the form a^n, where a is the base and n is an integer. For example, 2^3 = 2 × 2 × 2, 3^2 = 3 × 3, and 4^1 = 4.

In the problem, we are asked to check if an integer n is a power of three. One way to do this is to use a while loop that keeps dividing n by 3 as long as n is divisible by 3. If n becomes 1, it means it is a power of three. If n becomes something other than 1, it means it is not a power of three.

Here is a Java solution that uses a while loop to check if an integer is a power of three:

```java
public class PowerOfThree {
    public boolean isPowerOfThree(int n) {
        if (n <= 0) {
            return false;
        }
        while (n % 3 == 0) {
            n = n / 3;
        }
        return n == 1;
    }
}
```

This solution has a time complexity of O(log(n)), where n is the input integer. This is because in the worst case, the loop will iterate log(n) times, where log(n) is the exponent that satisfies n = 3^log(n).

